@Jerry

Are you talking about them walking point in a combat area? Just curious. Will just note that in my company (in the 101st) we were almost always out in the jungle. Which meant that you really couldn't see very far in front of where you were walking. So... walking point was a bit of risky business. That's why just about everyone had their turn doing it. 

....

@Rich in Atlanta
Patrolling in Jungle warfare operations was taught for many years, with lessons learned from Vietnam. It continued to prove useful in close order combat situations like Bosnia, Honduras, Afghanistan etc. Not so much in open desert and arctic warfare. It is a useful tactic in movement to contact in dismounted operations, whether the plt. is delivered by bird, track, or air insertion.
Point is a position that is earned through trust and skill, even in urban warfare. If “the LT” proves worthy, then yes. In spec ops, everyone learns point. It may not be called that in modern conventional warfare (whatever that means anymore), but it’s a thing.

